eyword><keyword weight="0.46263">Computer science</keyword><keyword weight="0.45927">Operations research</keyword><keyword weight="0.75175">Two-level scheduling</keyword><keyword weight="0.62876">Scheduling (production processes)</keyword><keyword weight="0.6383">Nurse scheduling problem</keyword><keyword weight="0.65418">Genetic algorithm scheduling</keyword><keyword weight="0.73059">Rate-monotonic scheduling</keyword><keyword weight="0.73972">Dynamic priority scheduling</keyword></keywords><publisher>Elsevier</publisher><abstract>Abstract Efficient scheduling techniques of computing resources are essential for achieving satisfactory performance for users as computer systems and their applications become more complex. In this paper, we survey research on scheduling algorithms, review previous classifications of scheduling problems and present a broader classification scheme. Using a uniform terminology for scheduling strategies and the new classification scheme, previous work on scheduling strategies is reviewed and trends in scheduling research are identified. Finally, a methodology for developing scheduling strategies is presented.</abstract></paper>